        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down,</placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 27, 1879.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am glad to hear about the Vines, but it will take some years before any one can feel secure about the new varieties. Nevertheless there would be a better chance with the Vine than with the Potato, as other closely allied American species are phylloxera free.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I trust that you may be able to continue your admirable potato work, even if you do not receive Government aid. I have heard nothing: I know that Mr. Farrer has had two communications with Ld. Sandon on the subject; I heard from two officials that he is one of those men who cannot make up their minds what to do.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It is enough to sicken one to see how politicians waste their time in squabbling and neglect doing any good.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12370.xml">letter from James Torbitt, 25 December 1879</ref> and n. 1. Torbitt had announced that he had received a phylloxera-resistant vine from Portugal.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had been trying to secure government aid for Torbitt in his work on breeding blight-resistant potatoes. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1599.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Henry Farrer</ref> had offered to lay the case before <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7348.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Dudley Francis Stuart Ryder</ref>, Viscount Sandon (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12326.xml">letter to James Torbitt, 17 November 1879</ref>). The officials have not been identified.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">A note at the end of the copy reads, ‘the rest of this letter is cut away’.</note>
        </div>
    
